  "prompt": "How is a 2D seismic survey different from a 3D seismic survey?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between 2D and 3D seismic surveys:\n\n2D Seismic Survey:\n- Creates a single, linear cross-sectional image of the subsurface\n- Provides a simplified, two-dimensional representation of geological structures\n- Less expensive and faster to acquire\n- Lower resolution and less detailed\n- Used for initial exploration and preliminary geological mapping\n- Collects data along a single line or series of parallel lines\n- Limited ability to detect complex geological features\n\n3D Seismic Survey:\n- Creates a three-dimensional volumetric image of the subsurface\n- Provides a comprehensive, detailed view of geological structures\n- More expensive and time-consuming to acquire\n- Higher resolution and more precise\n- Used for detailed reservoir characterization and development\n- Collects data across a grid of lines in multiple directions\n- Better at identifying complex geological structures and potential hydrocarbon traps\n- Allows for more accurate interpretation of rock layers and potential drilling locations\n- Provides more comprehensive information for exploration and production planning\n\nThe primary difference is that 3D surveys offer a much more detailed and comprehensive view of subsurface geology compared to 2D surveys, enabling more accurate exploration and production strategies.",
